Think of GitHub as the online home for your code project.

If Codex gives you HTML, CSS, and JavaScript, that code has to live somewhere in an organized way so you can:

save it

edit it later

track changes

connect it to hosting

share it with developers or tools

deploy it to a live website

That is what GitHub is mainly for.

What GitHub is meant for
GitHub is a website built around Git, which is a version control system.

For a no-code beginner, the easiest way to think about it is:

Your computer folder holds your project locally

GitHub holds a cloud copy of that project

Git keeps track of every change you make over time

So GitHub is not where you “write HTML” by itself. It is where you store, organize, and manage the files that make up your app or website.

Why you need files after coding HTML/CSS/JS
When you build a frontend, the code is usually split into files like this:

index.html → the page structure

style.css → the design and layout

script.js → the logic and interactions

Those files are what the browser reads to display your website.

So after Codex generates code, you need to put that code into actual files because browsers and hosting platforms work with files, not just chat responses.

For example:

index.html
style.css
script.js
Without creating these files, you do not really have a working project yet. You only have code snippets.

Why create a GitHub repository
A repository is just a project folder on GitHub.

You create a GitHub repo so that:

all your frontend files live in one place

you can back them up online

you can connect the repo to hosting platforms like Vercel, Netlify, or GitHub Pages

you can update the site later without starting over

other tools can pull from it

So the reason people say “create a GitHub repo” is really:

Create a structured online project folder for your code.

What happens after you get code from Codex
Here is the normal beginner flow:

1. Codex generates your frontend code
You may get:

HTML

CSS

JavaScript

sometimes React or Next.js files

2. You place the code into files
Example:

paste page structure into index.html

paste styling into style.css

paste interactivity into script.js

3. You save those files in a project folder
Example folder:

my-frontend-project/
  index.html
  style.css
  script.js
4. You upload that folder to GitHub
Now the project is stored online.

5. You connect GitHub to a hosting platform
This makes your frontend live on the internet.

6. You connect the frontend to Xano
Your frontend starts sending and receiving data from Xano using APIs.

Simple picture of the whole setup
Think of it like this:

Frontend = what users see and click

Xano = where your data and logic live

GitHub = where your frontend code is stored

Hosting platform = where your frontend becomes a real website

So the flow is:

Codex writes code → you save it into files → upload to GitHub → deploy frontend → connect frontend to Xano

What GitHub does not do
GitHub is not your database.
GitHub is not your backend.
GitHub is not Xano.

GitHub mainly stores your code and helps you manage changes.

Why GitHub matters even for no-code or low-code users
Even if you are not a traditional developer, GitHub is useful because:

AI tools often generate code projects

many hosting platforms deploy directly from GitHub

it becomes easier to keep versions

you avoid losing files

future developers can understand your project

So even in a no-code journey, GitHub becomes the bridge between “AI gave me code” and “my app is actually live.”

How frontend connects to Xano backend
Xano gives you API endpoints.

An API endpoint is like a web address your frontend can talk to.

Example:

Xano endpoint for login

Xano endpoint for getting tailors

Xano endpoint for submitting bookings

Xano endpoint for reviews

Your frontend JavaScript calls those endpoints.

Simple example
Your frontend might send a request like this:

fetch("https://your-xano-url.com/api:123/get_tailors")
  .then(response => response.json())
  .then(data => {
    console.log(data);
  });
What this means:

frontend asks Xano for data

Xano sends data back

frontend displays it on the page

So the frontend is the display layer, and Xano is the data/logic layer.

Beginner way to understand the connection
When a user clicks a button on your site, one of two things usually happens:

Case 1: Get data
Example:

user opens page

frontend asks Xano: “give me list of products”

Xano returns JSON

frontend shows products on screen

Case 2: Send data
Example:

user fills a form

frontend sends form data to Xano

Xano saves it to database

frontend shows success message

So your frontend code is basically a messenger between the user and Xano.

What you need from Xano to connect it
Usually you need:

the API base URL

the specific endpoints

request type: GET, POST, PUT, DELETE

required headers

auth token if login is needed

request body format

Example:

GET /tailors

POST /login

POST /reviews

GET /auth/me

Where GitHub fits in this Xano connection
GitHub stores the frontend code that contains those API calls.

For example, in your script.js or React files, you may have:

login logic

fetch user profile logic

submit booking logic

load tailor details logic

That frontend code lives in GitHub, while the actual data handling happens in Xano.

Very simple real-world analogy
Imagine you are building a restaurant system:

Frontend = dining area where customers place orders

Xano = kitchen and food storage

GitHub = the building plan stored safely

Hosting = the actual restaurant location people visit

Customers do not see GitHub.
They interact with the frontend.
The frontend talks to Xano.

