Do I need to use codex in vs code or can I stick to web version? Also, I hear I can create tasks for different parts of the project. What is the best way to use codex?


Thought for 7s
Yes — you can stick to the web version of Codex. You do not have to use VS Code to get started. OpenAI’s docs say you can use Codex in the browser by going to the Codex web app and connecting a GitHub repository as your environment. 

The main difference is this:

Codex web is great for delegating work: “build this page,” “clean up these files,” “connect this form to my API,” “review this repo,” and similar task-based work. OpenAI describes Codex web as a cloud agent that can read, edit, and run code in its own cloud environment, and it can handle tasks in parallel. 

VS Code with the Codex extension is better when you want to work side by side with the code, inspect files manually, run the app locally, and make quick edits while seeing everything in an IDE. OpenAI says the extension lets you use Codex in your IDE or delegate tasks to Codex Cloud. 

Codex CLI is another option for more technical users who want Codex to work directly in a local folder from the terminal. 

For your situation as a no-code beginner using Codex + GitHub + Xano, the best starting point is the web version. It is simpler, less overwhelming, and matches the way you want to think in tasks rather than files and terminal commands. The official quickstart explicitly supports using Codex in the browser and connecting a GitHub repo there. 

How to think about “tasks”
Yes, creating separate tasks for different parts of the project is a smart way to use Codex. OpenAI describes Codex as a task-oriented coding agent, and the Codex app supports multitasking across projects. 

The best way to use tasks is to make each one small and specific. Do not give Codex one giant instruction like:

“Build my whole app.”

That usually creates confusion.

Instead, split the work into focused tasks like:

Set up project structure
“Create the frontend structure for a Xano-connected web app. Add folders for pages, components, styles, and scripts.”

Build one page at a time
“Create a login page with email, password, validation, and clean styling.”

Connect one endpoint at a time
“Connect the login form to my Xano login endpoint and store the auth token.”

Add the next feature
“Create a dashboard page that calls /auth/me and displays the logged-in user.”

Clean and review
“Refactor the frontend so API URLs are stored in one config file.”

Test and fix
“Find and fix high-confidence bugs in the login flow.”

That task-by-task approach works better because Codex is good at completing concrete engineering tasks end to end, and OpenAI’s own examples also emphasize working in bounded tasks like building a feature, fixing bugs, or understanding a project. 

Best setup for you
For where you are right now, this is the setup I’d recommend:

Phase 1: Use Codex web + GitHub

Create or connect your repo

Let Codex create and organize the frontend

Use separate tasks for each page and feature

Ask it to connect to Xano endpoint by endpoint

Phase 2: Move to VS Code only when needed
Use VS Code later if you reach the point where you want to:

run the app locally

inspect file-by-file changes more comfortably

debug JavaScript in more detail

manually tweak code faster

That is because the VS Code extension is meant for working side by side in the IDE, while the web version is already enough for delegated coding work. 

